I'm not going to explain this one because
you're on the Internet, so I assume that you've

00:02:47.510 --> 00:02:52.430
already seen how adorable it is to watch babies
destroy stuff, instead, I'm gonna demonstrate.

00:02:52.430 --> 00:02:56.030
So I am a father, I've seen children do this
a lot.

00:02:56.030 --> 00:03:01.120
Basically you just go in and you just..

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:05.410
Then you go...

00:03:05.410 --> 00:03:07.090
That's basically it.

00:03:07.090 --> 00:03:11.450
In additions to punches, Canadians have been
known to spread butter on the nose of the

00:03:11.450 --> 00:03:12.450
birthday person.

00:03:12.450 --> 00:03:15.710
Mark, I know that you're Canadian, but please
don't make me do this one because I just finished

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:17.660
cleaning myself up after the smash cake.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:22.240
Similarly, it's considered good luck in Nepal
to put colored rice yogurt on your forehead

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:23.240
for birthdays.

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:27.980
Mexicans have a special birthday song, \'93Las
Mananitas (aka "The Little Mornings") which

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:31.030
is usually sung at a party before the group
eats cake.

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:34.810
And of course, pinatas are a common way to
celebrate a birthday in Mexico.

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:38.730
Although we usually think of them as Mexican,
pinatas actually originated in China and were

00:03:38.730 --> 00:03:40.230
used to celebrate New Years.

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:42.840
It was Europeans who eventually brought them
over to Mexico.

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:47.180
In Ghana, a traditional birthday dish is oto
- mashed yams with eggs and onions.

00:03:47.180 --> 00:03:50.290
In China, Yi mein is commonly eaten on birthdays.

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:52.870
In English, those are
Longevity noodles" or

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:54.010
long life noodles."

00:03:54.010 --> 00:03:57.350
Also, be sure to avoid giving a watch or a
clock as a gift in China.

00:03:57.350 --> 00:03:59.240
These are considered bad luck.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:01.590
Celebrating individual birthdays is rare in
Vietnam.

00:04:01.590 --> 00:04:05.650
Instead, all birthdays are celebrated on the
Vietnamese holiday of Tet, which is a New

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:07.000
Years celebration.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.190
Children do receive gifts though!

00:04:08.190 --> 00:04:11.440
Their elders give them red envelopes with
money inside.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:15.820
Korea operates somewhat similarly - first
birthdays are celebrated, but subsequent birthdays

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:17.660
are all celebrated on the New Year.

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:21.500
Wishing someone "happy birthday" before their
actual birthday is considered bad luck in

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:22.500
Germany.

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:26.320
On someone's 16th birthday in Germany, they
may have flour thrown on their head, which

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:31.340
may sound rough, but in Jamaica, throwing
flour on the head is an every birthday tradition,

00:04:31.340 --> 00:04:32.750
not just a one time thing.

00:04:32.750 --> 00:04:36.590
I'm not going to throw flour on anyone's head
here, but I will demonstrate with a doll.

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:37.590
Happy Birthday, Yoda.

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:39.370
What are you, like, a thousand now?

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:44.000
Anyway, back to Germany...On 18th birthdays,
the flour is replaced with eggs.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.050
And if a man reaches his 25th birthday before
he marries, his friends will hang a "sockencranz,"

00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:52.210
or sock wreath, outside of his house.

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:54.960
The "old socks" are a symbol of his old age.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:58.460
On that note, some cultures have different
traditions for when people turn a certain

00:04:58.460 --> 00:04:59.460
age.

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:01.930
Like, you probably already know that girls
who practice Judaism have bat mitzvah when

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:05.770
they turn 12 and boys have a bar mitzvah when
they turn 13.

00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:08.310
Those ceremonies represent a move into adulthood.

00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:10.230
Let's finish up with some more age-specific
traditions.

00:05:10.230 --> 00:05:13.860
I'm sure you've also heard of a Quinceanera...especially
if you were spending all of your free time

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:16.270
watching "My Super Sweet 16" in 2005.

00:05:16.270 --> 00:05:18.440
I'm not pointing any fingers, Meredith.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:22.710
In South Africa, when a person turns 21, their
parents present them with a key that symbolizes

00:05:22.710 --> 00:05:24.840
responsibility and the future.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:30.840
In Holland, they celebrate "crown years,"
which are the ages 5, 10, 15, 20, and 21.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:33.120
On those birthdays, you get bigger presents.

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:37.100
The 1st, 5th, 10th, and 15th birthdays are
the most important in Nigeria.

00:05:37.100 --> 00:05:41.380
Up to 100 people might show up to those celebrations,
which usually involve a feast.

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:45.900
For boys who practice Orthodox Judaism and
Hasidic Judaism, the third birthday is important

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:48.580
because it's the day they receive their first
haircut.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:52.350
In fact, that tradition has now spread in
Israel and doesn't always apply only to religious

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:53.350
people.

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:56.850
Similarly, people from the Indian island of
Minicoy shave their newborn baby's head after

00:05:56.850 --> 00:05:57.850
twenty days.

00:05:57.850 --> 00:05:59.300
Then, the hair is weighed.

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:03.320
Whatever the weight is will be given to charity
in silver or gold.

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:05.650
That's not a birthday thing, really, we just
thought it was cool.

